  "prompt": "How do I register my business in the U.K.?",
  "response": "Registering your business in the UK depends on the type of business structure you choose:\n\n**1. Sole Trader:**\n\n*   **Simplest Structure:** You and your business are considered the same legal entity.\n*   **Registration:** You don't formally \"register\" a sole trader business with Companies House. However, you *must* register with **HMRC (Her Majesty's Revenue and Customs)** for tax purposes.\n\n    *   **How to Register with HMRC:**\n        *   Go to the GOV.UK website and search for \"Register as self-employed.\"\n        *   You'll need to create a Government Gateway account if you don't already have one.\n        *   Provide details about yourself and your business, including your National Insurance number.\n        *   You'll receive a Unique Taxpayer Reference (UTR) number, which you'll need for filing your Self Assessment tax return.\n\n*   **Key Considerations:**\n    *   You are personally liable for all business debts.\n    *   You pay Income Tax on your profits.\n    *   You need to keep accurate records of your income and expenses.\n\n**2. Partnership:**\n\n*   **Two or More People:**  You and your partners share responsibility for the business.\n*   **Registration:** Similar to sole traders, partnerships don't formally register with Companies House. You *must* register with HMRC for tax purposes.\n\n    *   **How to Register with HMRC:**\n        *   One partner registers the partnership for Self Assessment.  Go to GOV.UK and search for \"Register a partnership for Self Assessment.\"\n        *   Each partner must register individually for Self Assessment.\n        *   You'll need details about the partnership agreement, partners' personal information, and a nominated partner for correspondence.\n        *   The partnership will receive a UTR, and each partner will have their own.\n\n*   **Key Considerations:**\n    *   Partners are jointly and severally liable for the business debts (meaning each partner is responsible for the full amount, even if caused by another partner).\n    *   You pay Income Tax on your share of the profits.\n    *   A written partnership agreement is highly recommended to define roles, responsibilities, profit sharing, and dispute resolution.\n\n**3. Limited Company (Ltd):**\n\n*   **Separate Legal Entity:** The company is distinct from its owners (shareholders) and managers (directors).  This offers *limited liability*, meaning your personal assets are generally protected from business debts.\n*   **Registration:** You **must** register your limited company with **Companies House**.\n\n    *   **How to Register with Companies House:**\n        *   **Online Registration (Fastest):**  Use the Companies House online service. You'll need to create an account.\n        *   **Third-Party Software:** Use Companies House-approved software.  Many accounting software packages offer company formation services.\n        *   **Paper Forms (Slower):**  Download and complete the required forms from the Companies House website and mail them in.\n\n    *   **Information Required:**\n        *   **Company Name:**  Must be unique and end with \"Limited\" or \"Ltd.\"  Check the Companies House register to avoid duplication.\n        *   **Registered Office Address:**  The official address for correspondence.\n        *   **Director(s):**  Details of the people who will manage the company.  At least one director is required.\n        *   **Shareholder(s):**  Details of the people who own the company shares.  A director can also be a shareholder.\n        *   **Memorandum of Association:**  States that the initial shareholders wish to form a company and agree to become members. This is usually a standard document.\n        *   **Articles of Association:**  Sets out the rules for running the company. You can use model articles provided by Companies House or create your own.\n        *   **Standard Industrial Classification (SIC) Code:**  Describes the company's business activities.\n        *   **Statement of Initial Significant Control (PSC):** Details of anyone who has significant control over the company. This is usually the directors or shareholders.\n\n    *   **Fees:**  There is a fee to register a limited company, which varies depending on the method used (online is usually cheaper). Check the Companies House website for current fees.\n\n    *   **After Registration:**\n        *   You'll receive a Certificate of Incorporation, confirming the company's registration.\n        *   You'll receive a Company Registration Number (CRN).\n        *   You *must* register with HMRC for Corporation Tax within three months of starting to trade.\n        *   If you employ people, you must register as an employer with HMRC.\n\n*   **Key Considerations:**\n    *   More complex to set up and administer than sole trader or partnership.\n    *   Must file annual accounts and a confirmation statement with Companies House.\n    *   Must pay Corporation Tax on profits.\n    *   Offers limited liability, protecting personal assets.\n    *   May be more attractive to investors.\n\n**Where to Start:**\n\n1.  **Choose Your Business Structure:** This is the most important decision.  Consider the level of risk you're willing to take, the complexity you can handle, and the tax implications.\n2.  **Check Name Availability:**  For a limited company, use the Companies House website to check if your desired company name is available.\n3.  **Gather Required Information:**  Collect all the necessary details about yourself, your partners (if applicable), and your business.\n4.  **Register Online:**  The online registration process is generally the quickest and easiest.\n\n**Important Tips & Resources:**\n\n*   **GOV.UK:**  The official UK government website is your primary source of information. Search for topics like \"start a business,\" \"register as self-employed,\" \"incorporate a company,\" \"corporation tax,\" etc.\n*   **Companies House:**  The registrar of companies in the UK.  [https://www.gov.uk/government/organisations/companies-house](https://www.gov.uk/government/organisations/companies-house)\n*   **HMRC (Her Majesty's Revenue and Customs):**  The UK's tax authority.\n*   **Accountant:**  Consider consulting an accountant for advice on business structure, tax planning, and compliance.  This is particularly helpful for limited companies.\n*   **Business Advisor:**  The government offers business support and advice through various organizations.  Search online for \"business support UK\" to find local resources.\n*   **Trademark Your Brand:** Consider registering your brand name and logo as trademarks to protect them. This is separate from company registration and is done through the Intellectual Property Office (IPO).\n\n**Summary Table:**\n\n| Feature          | Sole Trader        | Partnership        | Limited Company (Ltd) |\n|-------------------|--------------------|--------------------|-----------------------|\n| Registration     | HMRC Only          | HMRC Only          | Companies House & HMRC|\n| Liability        | Unlimited          | Unlimited          | Limited               |\n| Tax              | Income Tax         | Income Tax         | Corporation Tax       |\n| Complexity       | Simplest           | Moderate           | Most Complex          |\n| Legal Entity      | No                 | No                 | Yes                   |\n| Annual Filing     | Self Assessment    | Self Assessment    | Annual Accounts & Confirmation Statement |\n\n**Disclaimer:** This information is for general guidance only and does not constitute professional legal or financial advice. It is essential to consult with relevant professionals before making any decisions about your business. Laws and regulations can change, so always verify the information with official sources.\n",
